00:02:58.019 --> 00:02:59.310
DEUKI HONG: Thanks [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:59.310 --> 00:03:01.090
MATT RODBARD: I've been a fan
of your writing for a long time.

00:03:01.090 --> 00:03:02.160
So thank you for
taking the time.

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:02.860
HILLARY: Vice versa.

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:03.901
MATT RODBARD: Absolutely.

00:03:03.901 --> 00:03:07.990
But Koreatown is really--
it's a place of course.

00:03:07.990 --> 00:03:09.446
There's Koreatowns
in most cities.

00:03:09.446 --> 00:03:11.320
But the way you really
think about Koreatown,

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:13.090
it's a mentality.

00:03:13.090 --> 00:03:16.640
You put two Korean markets
next to a Korean dry cleaner

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:21.010
next to a Korean restaurant
and you've got a Koreatown.

00:03:21.010 --> 00:03:23.000
That is everywhere.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.000
DEUKI HONG: At least
that's how we defined it.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:25.875
It's just very like--

00:03:25.875 --> 00:03:27.310
MATT RODBARD: It's
not like-- you

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:31.810
don't need 50,000 Koreans in
an area for it to be Koreatown.

00:03:31.810 --> 00:03:34.100
We found Koreatowns
through our travels

00:03:34.100 --> 00:03:36.660
over the course of the research
of this book, which was

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:38.330
about three and a half years.

00:03:38.330 --> 00:03:39.860
We found Koreatowns
in the expected

00:03:39.860 --> 00:03:41.760
places like New
York, where we live,

00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:44.850
and Los Angeles, which is the
biggest Koreatown in America.

00:03:44.850 --> 00:03:48.270
But we also found in places
like north Philadelphia

00:03:48.270 --> 00:03:51.970
and outside Chicago,
Minneapolis, Houston.

00:03:51.970 --> 00:03:54.850
Places that may be
aren't considered

00:03:54.850 --> 00:03:57.950
the Koreatown
epicenter of America.

00:03:57.950 --> 00:04:00.300
But really Koreatown
is more of a spirit.

00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:00.940
Right?

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:03.350
We talk about that a
lot when we're out.

00:04:03.350 --> 00:04:04.227
We talk Korean food.

00:04:04.227 --> 00:04:06.060
DEUKI HONG: I mean we
had to define it first

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:06.851
before we found it.

00:04:06.851 --> 00:04:10.660
I mean to his credit, it was
Matty that wrote the book--I

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:13.810
mean not wrote the book, that
came up with the whole concept

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:15.490
of Koreatown.

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:18.541
I remember asking him,
so what are we doing.

00:04:18.541 --> 00:04:19.540
And we had to define it.

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:21.081
And I think that's
how we defined it.

00:04:21.081 --> 00:04:23.300
Was really the mentality.

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:26.290
You know, like you said, if
you saw two Korean restaurants

00:04:26.290 --> 00:04:31.190
next to each other or we were
just in Madison, Wisconsin,

00:04:31.190 --> 00:04:34.820
an adopted Korean chef has
just a Korean restaurant

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:37.019
in the middle of
Madison, Wisconsin.

00:04:37.019 --> 00:04:38.310
That embodies really Koreatown.

00:04:38.310 --> 00:04:40.390
MATT RODBARD: That's
Koreatown right there.

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:42.380
And we'll get into
other parts of Koreatown

00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:45.820
through the conversation which
may be a little unexpected too.

00:04:45.820 --> 00:04:47.530
HILLARY: Yeah, for sure.

00:04:47.530 --> 00:04:51.870
So for people who haven't got it
chance to open their books yet,

00:04:51.870 --> 00:04:55.396
one of the really unusual
things about the presentation

00:04:55.396 --> 00:04:56.770
and the structure
of this book is

00:04:56.770 --> 00:05:01.820
that there's a pretty typical
cookbook structure, especially

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:04.390
cookbooks that are tied to
restaurant chefs like Deuki.

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:07.360
Where it's got an intro, and
you have a recipe header where

00:05:07.360 --> 00:05:09.680
it's usually a story about
why this dish is meaningful,

00:05:09.680 --> 00:05:11.430
the story of the dish
ended up on the menu.

00:05:11.430 --> 00:05:12.480
You have the recipe
and then either

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:13.770
on the left side
or the right side

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:15.130
will be a picture of the dish.

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:17.470
And that is not what your
guys' book looks like.

00:05:17.470 --> 00:05:20.670
And how does the structure
of the book to you

00:05:20.670 --> 00:05:23.300
reflect that Koreatown spirit.

00:05:23.300 --> 00:05:24.980
MATT RODBARD: It's
a really good point.

00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:27.980
When we signed our
contract, we really

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:29.950
didn't know what we were doing.

00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:32.330
We aren't cookbook authors.

00:05:32.330 --> 00:05:36.390
Are you not a cookbook
chef or a recipe developer.

00:05:36.390 --> 00:05:38.177
I knew magazine.

00:05:38.177 --> 00:05:40.110
I knew web journalism.

00:05:40.110 --> 00:05:41.290
I knew packaging.

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:44.940
And I really wanted
us to do a book that

00:05:44.940 --> 00:05:49.380
brought the energy and
spirit of Koreatown to life.

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:51.880
So to do that we
needed to look outward.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:54.620
It wasn't just repeating
recipes from your family

00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:55.990
and from our friends.

00:05:55.990 --> 00:05:57.825
We had to go out and
actually find them.

00:05:57.825 --> 00:05:59.700
And you see that in the
structure of the book

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:00.580
as we were reporting.

00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:02.950
We like to think that we
went and talked to people

00:06:02.950 --> 00:06:05.010
and ran the recorder
and ran our iPhones

00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:06.900
and talked for several
hours and went back

00:06:06.900 --> 00:06:09.780
to those conversations and
figured out a story from then.

00:06:09.780 --> 00:06:12.330
That's kind of the way we look
at the Koreatown as a book.

00:06:12.330 --> 00:06:15.690
As more of cultural
anthropology of sorts.

00:06:15.690 --> 00:06:19.710
You know, it's not just
the recipe, head note,

00:06:19.710 --> 00:06:21.950
circle plate, circle
plate, circle plate, photo

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:24.040
that you see in a
lot of cookbooks.

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:25.680
Nothing against circle plates.

00:06:25.680 --> 00:06:26.370
DEUKI HONG: We
have circle plates.

00:06:26.370 --> 00:06:28.203
MATT RODBARD: We do
have some circle plates.

00:06:28.203 --> 00:06:29.980
But if you look
visually at the book,

00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:32.120
it has all these
elements of travel.

00:06:32.120 --> 00:06:34.070
And we committed the
time and resources

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:37.180
to travel to answer
the question, what

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:40.290
is Koreatown both visually
and through the recipes.

00:06:40.290 --> 00:06:42.430
It's not the easiest
way to do a cookbook.

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:44.471
DEUKI HONG: I mean we just
don't know what to do.

00:06:44.471 --> 00:06:47.275
We really didn't know
what we were doing.

00:06:47.275 --> 00:06:52.130
I think it's great that it's
not like Deuki's 101 Recipes

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:54.440
or Korean Cooking
Like Made Simple.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:57.219
Like we didn't know
what we were doing.

00:06:57.219 --> 00:06:58.010
MATT RODBARD: Yeah.

00:06:58.010 --> 00:07:01.392
DEUKI HONG: And I think
out of that naivete--

00:07:01.392 --> 00:07:02.225
which is a big word.

00:07:02.225 --> 00:07:03.433
MATT RODBARD: Good job, Chef.

00:07:03.433 --> 00:07:05.110
DEUKI HONG: Thank you.

00:07:05.110 --> 00:07:07.260
We just did it like for us.

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:11.290
Our approach was-- he has
a magazine background.

00:07:11.290 --> 00:07:14.400
So if you see the layout,
there's like stories in it,

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:16.610
there's a Q&amp;A in there.

00:07:16.610 --> 00:07:19.980
So I personally love the layout.

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:21.970
I just think, I
think I love my book.

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:23.062
MATT RODBARD: Yeah.

00:07:23.062 --> 00:07:25.020
DEUKI HONG: But you know
it's just fun to read.

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:29.250
And I like that it's not
like stews, and then barbecue

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:30.940
and you know.

00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:33.060
For me, that's kind
of the biggest draw.

00:07:33.060 --> 00:07:36.010
We have a respect section
at the end of the book which

00:07:36.010 --> 00:07:41.070
is a lot of really awesome chefs
that just love Korean food,

00:07:41.070 --> 00:07:43.100
support Korean food.

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:45.200
That's like my favorite
section of the book.

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:50.640
And like how you guys
would cook food--

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:51.860
we made the book like that.

00:07:51.860 --> 00:07:54.376
We went to H-mart.

00:07:54.376 --> 00:07:56.000
MATT RODBARD: H-Mart,
which is like one

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:57.470
of the main Korean
markets in the east coast.

00:07:57.470 --> 00:08:00.260
DEUKI HONG: H-Mart, went to my
apartment and started cooking.

00:08:00.260 --> 00:08:02.940
That's literally how those
recipes have been developed.

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:03.320
MATT RODBARD: It's true.

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:04.403
DEUKI HONG: It's very raw.

00:08:04.403 --> 00:08:07.390
HILLARY: So speaking more to
the recipe development process,

00:08:07.390 --> 00:08:09.590
I'd love to get into the
nuts and bolts of how

00:08:09.590 --> 00:08:10.861
this book came together.

00:08:10.861 --> 00:08:12.610
You guys have spoken
a lot about this sort

00:08:12.610 --> 00:08:14.580
of like going in blind.

00:08:14.580 --> 00:08:18.350
How did the book
deal come about?

00:08:18.350 --> 00:08:21.640
And how did you
start dividing up

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:22.850
the labor between yourselves?

00:08:22.850 --> 00:08:24.430
MATT RODBARD: Good question.

00:08:24.430 --> 00:08:27.830
Well we met actually
working on a separate book.

00:08:27.830 --> 00:08:30.610
A smaller guidebook to Korean
restaurants in New York.

00:08:30.610 --> 00:08:33.289
We went to 75
Korean restaurants.

00:08:33.289 --> 00:08:34.809
Yeah you were like, whoa.

00:08:34.809 --> 00:08:37.544
And you know, what most
of them are not very good.

00:08:37.544 --> 00:08:38.710
DEUKI HONG: That's not nice.

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:41.054
MATT RODBARD: I
know it's not nice.

00:08:41.054 --> 00:08:43.179
All right, some of them
were not very good.

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:45.695
We were tasked with going
to a lot of different styles

00:08:45.695 --> 00:08:46.320
of restaurants.

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:47.840
And it wasn't just
the greatest hits.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:49.840
There was definitely some
out-of-the-way places.

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:51.600
And we met through
that project where

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:55.010
we had to really define
these restaurants.

00:08:55.010 --> 00:08:57.810
We rated them, as if we
were in the Michelin Guide.

00:08:57.810 --> 00:09:00.460
We had to go in like
check off a bunch of boxes

00:09:00.460 --> 00:09:01.600
and rate these restaurants.

00:09:01.600 --> 00:09:04.920
And really we met
through that process.

00:09:04.920 --> 00:09:07.410
And we came to the
conclusion that there is not

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:10.850
a book written from the
point of view of Koreatown.

00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:12.810
I bought every book I
could when I was writing

00:09:12.810 --> 00:09:14.268
that small guidebook
and I saw they

00:09:14.268 --> 00:09:18.450
were written from the point of
a food professor from Korea.

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:20.800
Or from a YouTube star.

00:09:20.800 --> 00:09:21.300
Maangchi.

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:21.800
She's great.

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:23.670
And we love Maangchi.

00:09:23.670 --> 00:09:25.860
I've watched hundreds
hours of Maangchi

00:09:25.860 --> 00:09:27.930
while researching Korean food.

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:29.210
But we aren't Maangchi.

00:09:29.210 --> 00:09:31.900
We are more, as we said
before, journalists and chef.

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:34.420
So we realized there
wasn't this book written.

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:35.870
So what do you do.

00:09:35.870 --> 00:09:37.870
Well, you kind of have
to write a book proposal.

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:39.670
And that's really what we did.

00:09:39.670 --> 00:09:44.270
And we found, through our
great agent Angela Miller,

00:09:44.270 --> 00:09:47.830
a home at Clarkson Potter.

00:09:47.830 --> 00:09:49.620
Clarkson Potter is
a place that has

00:09:49.620 --> 00:09:52.330
done a lot of big name celebrity
chefs and some smaller titles

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:53.210
as well.

00:09:53.210 --> 00:09:57.270
But it was fortunate
that our book proposal

00:09:57.270 --> 00:10:00.782
landed on the desk of Francis
Lam, who Is out editor.

00:10:00.782 --> 00:10:02.240
And it was the
first book he signed

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:03.830
when he joined Clarkson Potter.

00:10:03.830 --> 00:10:08.130
And he really he shepherded
it through from the proposal

00:10:08.130 --> 00:10:09.610
phase all the way to the end.

00:10:09.610 --> 00:10:11.610
And you know I think
Francis was a big part of--

00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:12.818
DEUKI HONG: Yeah, FL's great.

00:10:12.818 --> 00:10:15.900
I mean he's great just
because he's Francis.

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:22.225
And the fact that we
were his first-- we're

00:10:22.225 --> 00:10:23.760
like the proverbial nobodies.

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:25.710
And for him, he could
have gotten a deal

00:10:25.710 --> 00:10:28.920
from-- he can choose whatever
chef he wants to work with.

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:30.600
Whatever writer or
whatever personality

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:31.270
he wants to work with.

00:10:31.270 --> 00:10:33.000
And he really believed
in the project.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.252
And I think because he
believed in it-- like we always

00:10:35.252 --> 00:10:37.460
believed in it because we
can just toot our own horns

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:38.990
because we're so awesome.

00:10:38.990 --> 00:10:42.304
And when you get somebody like
Francis, like this is awesome.

00:10:42.304 --> 00:10:43.720
Then you start
really believing it

00:10:43.720 --> 00:10:47.040
and then I think
that becomes passion.

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:49.910
That becomes, OK, we
can go to that city.

00:10:49.910 --> 00:10:52.160
And that kind of gets me going.

00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:55.290
Like, FL is kind of like
my like spirit animal.

00:10:55.290 --> 00:10:56.980
It's like, hey,
he believes in us.

00:10:56.980 --> 00:10:59.094
HILLARY: And that's what
an editor does, right?

00:10:59.094 --> 00:11:00.010
MATT RODBARD: He does.

00:11:00.010 --> 00:11:00.801
He sees it through.

00:11:00.801 --> 00:11:03.790
And he shows that he's
committed to our idea.

00:11:03.790 --> 00:11:07.090
And I'll say, we didn't
have a million offers.

00:11:07.090 --> 00:11:08.141
We had multiple offers.

00:11:08.141 --> 00:11:09.640
But we didn't have
a million offers.

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:10.740
DEUKI HONG: And
we had two offers.

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:11.930
MATT RODBARD: Yeah
we had a few offers.

00:11:11.930 --> 00:11:12.596
DEUKI HONG: Two.

00:11:12.596 --> 00:11:15.770
MATT RODBARD: And you know
it was honestly something

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:21.290
that we give credit to Francis
for seeing Korean food's

00:11:21.290 --> 00:11:24.240
rise maybe two or
three years ago,

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:26.370
when he signed the contracts.

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:31.512
HILLARY: So I want to go back
to some cookbook contacts.

00:11:31.512 --> 00:11:33.220
When you look at the
cover of a cookbook,

00:11:33.220 --> 00:11:35.845
including the Koreatown cookbook
that you have in front of you,

00:11:35.845 --> 00:11:38.420
the way that the
authorship is built

00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:40.310
is very coded with meaning.

00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:42.870
So this book could
have been Deuki Hong

00:11:42.870 --> 00:11:46.890
with Matt Rodbard-- could
have been the way it ended up.

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:48.740
It could have just
said Deuki Hong

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:51.340
and then maybe somewhere
inside the book

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:54.910
it would have explained
that Matt existed.

00:11:54.910 --> 00:11:58.020
Sometimes chef-driven
cookbooks don't

00:11:58.020 --> 00:11:59.520
have a writer listed anywhere.

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:03.230
And it's an industry secret,
you know who worked on it.

00:12:03.230 --> 00:12:05.246
And your guys'
cookbook-- flat out you

00:12:05.246 --> 00:12:06.370
guys are on the same level.

00:12:06.370 --> 00:12:08.066
It says Deuki Hong
and Matt Rodbard.

00:12:08.066 --> 00:12:09.690
Can you explain a
little bit about what

00:12:09.690 --> 00:12:14.420
that means, both symbolically
and like practically speaking?

00:12:14.420 --> 00:12:15.980
MATT RODBARD: We are a team.

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:17.440
It really means that.

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:20.890
We could not write this
book without each other.

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:24.800
It's truly the best
kind of partnership.

00:12:24.800 --> 00:12:26.900
I'm not a hired gun
to write cookbooks.

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:29.610
And as you said, Deuki is
not like a celebrity TV chef.

00:12:29.610 --> 00:12:31.410
So we both needed each other.

00:12:31.410 --> 00:12:32.064
I need you.

00:12:32.064 --> 00:12:33.730
I needed to ask you
a million questions.

00:12:33.730 --> 00:12:35.710
DEUKI HONG: I wasn't
your first choice.

00:12:35.710 --> 00:12:36.484
I'm just saying.

00:12:36.484 --> 00:12:37.900
Just wanted to
throw it out there.

00:12:37.900 --> 00:12:40.246
MATT RODBARD: Any ways.

00:12:40.246 --> 00:12:41.700
Whatever.

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:43.390
DEUKI HONG: And
just to go on that.

00:12:43.390 --> 00:12:44.890
I think a lot of
people get confused

00:12:44.890 --> 00:12:46.640
because it is a Korean book.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:48.120
Or Koreatown book.

00:12:48.120 --> 00:12:51.180
They think the Korean guy on the
project kind of spearheaded it.

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:52.737
This is all his brainchild.

00:12:52.737 --> 00:12:54.570
And I just kind of
hopped on and I was like,

00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:56.360
oh yeah dude, that's awesome.

00:12:56.360 --> 00:12:59.340
What do you need from me.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:03.890
You know, he's not Korean
if you didn't realize.

00:13:03.890 --> 00:13:05.200
He is pretty much Korean.

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:11.840
But for us-- and we said in
the earlier conversation--

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:12.960
we're friends also.

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:13.780
MATT RODBARD: Yeah it's true.

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:16.196
DEUKI HONG: We're not like,
we don't clock in and be like,

00:13:16.196 --> 00:13:17.800
all right, let's do this event.

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:18.670
We talk.

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:19.630
We talk outside stuff.

00:13:19.630 --> 00:13:21.990
And we've developed
a friendship.

00:13:21.990 --> 00:13:24.230
We traveled for
two years together.

00:13:24.230 --> 00:13:27.180
Even if you hate
each other, it's just

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:28.810
out of like that relationship.

00:13:28.810 --> 00:13:31.495
And I think that genuine
friendship kind of gives it

00:13:31.495 --> 00:13:33.660
a better product.

00:13:33.660 --> 00:13:35.521
I didn't want to disappoint him.

00:13:35.521 --> 00:13:37.270
Hopefully he didn't
want to disappoint me.

00:13:37.270 --> 00:13:37.480
MATT RODBARD: Yeah.

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:38.680
DEUKI HONG: There was
that mutual respect.

00:13:38.680 --> 00:13:40.290
MATT RODBARD: We didn't want
to disappoint our publisher.

00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:41.850
And we didn't want
to disappoint--

00:13:41.850 --> 00:13:42.450
DEUKI HONG: It was
just a lot of that.

00:13:42.450 --> 00:13:43.741
MATT RODBARD: Korean-Americans.

00:13:43.741 --> 00:13:46.140
Koreans who-- and we'll
talk about the food.

00:13:46.140 --> 00:13:48.280
The food is so important
and we didn't really--

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:50.710
we needed to make sure we got
the right recipes in there.

00:13:50.710 --> 00:13:53.210
We wanted to make sure we got
the right head notes in there.

00:13:53.210 --> 00:13:56.520
And that each of these recipes
had the story it really exists.

00:13:56.520 --> 00:13:58.790
DEUKI HONG: This book
wasn't about Deuki or Matt.

00:13:58.790 --> 00:14:00.780
So it didn't matter what name.

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:03.940
Obviously nobody in this
room knows-- except my friend

00:14:03.940 --> 00:14:06.260
over there-- which is great.

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:06.860
Which is fine.

00:14:06.860 --> 00:14:09.390
Which is awesome because
it's really about the story.

00:14:09.390 --> 00:14:11.820
It's really about
what we want to tell

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:13.110
or the story we want to tell.

00:14:13.110 --> 00:14:16.270
And we always kind
of went back to that.

00:14:16.270 --> 00:14:20.320
You won't see our faces
except in our intro.

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:22.892
You won't see our faces
like plastered on this book.

00:14:22.892 --> 00:14:23.600
Nor should it be.

00:14:23.600 --> 00:14:24.391
MATT RODBARD: Yeah.

00:14:24.391 --> 00:14:27.970
DEUKI HONG: So it's our baby.

00:14:27.970 --> 00:14:28.965
You can approach it.

00:14:28.965 --> 00:14:31.090
MATT RODBARD: Any questions
at all in the audience?

00:14:31.090 --> 00:14:31.789
There you go.

00:14:31.789 --> 00:14:33.580
DEUKI HONG: It's like
a little study group.

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:35.832
Don't even-- get
a little intimate.

00:14:35.832 --> 00:14:38.102
AUDIENCE: I wanted to
hear a little more about--

00:14:38.102 --> 00:14:39.560
MATT RODBARD: So
the first question

00:14:39.560 --> 00:14:42.980
was, how did we come
together for that 75 project.

00:14:42.980 --> 00:14:46.090
And I'm reflecting on my answer
and I was a little harsh.

00:14:46.090 --> 00:14:47.996
I did not go to mostly
bad restaurants,

00:14:47.996 --> 00:14:49.620
I think that came
out very incorrectly.

00:14:49.620 --> 00:14:51.450
We went to a lot of
very good restaurants.

00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:53.520
We've been in
California for so long

00:14:53.520 --> 00:14:55.350
that the food in
California is so good.

00:14:55.350 --> 00:14:56.990
The Korean food here is amazing.

00:14:56.990 --> 00:14:59.690
So that's why I've got
a little hate towards.

00:14:59.690 --> 00:15:00.800
But I do love New York.

00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:03.029
So anyone in New York,
there are restaurants there

00:15:03.029 --> 00:15:03.820
that are very good.

00:15:03.820 --> 00:15:05.820
So we met on the project.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:07.660
It was funded by the
Korean government

00:15:07.660 --> 00:15:09.130
by the Korean Food Foundation.

00:15:09.130 --> 00:15:12.040
And they had that kind of vision
to create this guidebook, which

00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:15.470
was naming 35, 40 of the
best Korean restaurants.

00:15:15.470 --> 00:15:17.610
We met each other
through just dialog.

00:15:17.610 --> 00:15:19.280
Through talking
about our results.

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:21.530
We had this big meeting where
we went over the results

00:15:21.530 --> 00:15:23.500
and picked our top
30 restaurants.

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:24.506
So that's how we met.

00:15:24.506 --> 00:15:25.880
And then we
discontinued talking.

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:27.370
And I think we want to go
out and eat Korean food.

00:15:27.370 --> 00:15:29.578
Pretty much I was, hey, you
wanna grab some galbijjim

00:15:29.578 --> 00:15:30.270
and we went.

00:15:30.270 --> 00:15:32.380
And the other
question was about--

00:15:32.380 --> 00:15:34.130
HILLARY: It was
about your influences

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:37.150
and your personal story and
the influences that really

00:15:37.150 --> 00:15:40.390
comes through in your cooking.

00:15:40.390 --> 00:15:42.850
DEUKI HONG: I started
cooking pretty young.

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:45.200
Overall, my whole life,
I'm really blessed

00:15:45.200 --> 00:15:47.920
with a lot of-- I have a lot of
really cool people in my life.

00:15:47.920 --> 00:15:49.750
A lot of good people.

00:15:49.750 --> 00:15:52.502
That turned into really
cool opportunities.

00:15:52.502 --> 00:15:53.710
I played baseball growing up.

00:15:53.710 --> 00:15:57.480
My baseball coach was
partners with Drew Nieporent,

00:15:57.480 --> 00:16:02.820
who is the guy who is head
of Myriad Restaurant Group.

00:16:02.820 --> 00:16:06.956
Who'd started Nobu and that
whole-- they're like icons.

00:16:06.956 --> 00:16:08.330
And obviously, I
don't know that.

00:16:08.330 --> 00:16:12.280
He was like, if you like
restaurants, come on in.

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:12.780
So I did.

00:16:12.780 --> 00:16:17.130
I literally just, every day,
starting from that point,

00:16:17.130 --> 00:16:20.410
I worked for Chef Aaron
Sanchez, he's on TV now

00:16:20.410 --> 00:16:23.150
and does his thing.

00:16:23.150 --> 00:16:25.620
But yeah, after that, every
day after high school,

00:16:25.620 --> 00:16:28.810
class would end, bus,
subway, into the restaurant.

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:29.570
So it was great.

00:16:29.570 --> 00:16:32.170
And there was just more like,
I just love the restaurant.

00:16:32.170 --> 00:16:34.830
Like I'm not one of those
guys that's like, oh

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:36.490
my gosh, like cucumbers.

00:16:36.490 --> 00:16:37.680
Hey Chef.

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:39.096
MATT RODBARD: Chef
just walked in.

00:16:39.662 --> 00:16:41.120
DEUKI HONG: Japchae
was on tonight.

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:43.980
MATT RODBARD: Yeah, the japchae
in the cafeteria was so good.

00:16:43.980 --> 00:16:45.929
The chef just walked
in from Google.

00:16:45.929 --> 00:16:46.970
DEUKI HONG: He's awesome.

00:16:46.970 --> 00:16:47.790
Thank you so much.

00:16:47.790 --> 00:16:51.930
Yeah That was kind of it.

00:16:51.930 --> 00:16:54.262
Chef was like, you
need formal training.

00:16:54.262 --> 00:16:55.780
I was like, I disagree.

00:16:55.780 --> 00:16:57.610
I'll just stick with
you for my life.

00:16:57.610 --> 00:16:59.150
And I went to culinary school.

00:16:59.150 --> 00:17:01.090
I met Chef David Chang.

00:17:01.090 --> 00:17:03.463
We both worked for DC.

00:17:03.463 --> 00:17:08.894
Hopefully he never sees
this because I fear him.

00:17:08.894 --> 00:17:10.310
I love him at the
same exact time.

00:17:10.310 --> 00:17:12.268
MATT RODBARD: Love and
fear your older brother.

00:17:12.268 --> 00:17:15.130
DEUKI HONG: But yeah, that
was my Momofuku experience.

00:17:15.130 --> 00:17:18.790
And then I did the whole fine
dining route with Jean-Georges.

00:17:18.790 --> 00:17:23.490
I just have so many like-- if
I had control of where I was

00:17:23.490 --> 00:17:25.770
or what people to
meet, I don't think I

00:17:25.770 --> 00:17:27.680
would have planned it that way.

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:29.840
But yeah, all my experiences
were really unique.

00:17:29.840 --> 00:17:32.006
I'm influenced by all the
people that I worked with.

00:17:32.006 --> 00:17:34.690
Forget if you're David
Chang's or the Jean-Georges

00:17:34.690 --> 00:17:35.690
of the world.

00:17:35.690 --> 00:17:38.070
Or if you're-- you know I
have 21 guys underneath me

00:17:38.070 --> 00:17:41.650
in my kitchen and they
inspire me just as much.

00:17:41.650 --> 00:17:43.140
It's all about people for me.

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:46.291
I don't go crazy over a cucumber
or like heirloom tomatoes.

00:17:46.291 --> 00:17:47.790
They're great and
they're delicious,

00:17:47.790 --> 00:17:53.760
but it's got to bigger
than that, I feel like.

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:56.300
HILLARY: So one of the things
you talk about in the book,

00:17:56.300 --> 00:18:02.630
in the intro, is about this
idea that a lot of Korean food

00:18:02.630 --> 00:18:04.270
happens in the home.

00:18:04.270 --> 00:18:07.020
That it's very much a
home-oriented cuisine.

00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:09.107
And I remember like
Matt, in your intro,

00:18:09.107 --> 00:18:11.190
you'd go to restaurants
and you'd be like texting,

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:12.410
not how [KOREAN] made it.

00:18:12.410 --> 00:18:14.024
You know, which is
Korean for grandma.

00:18:14.024 --> 00:18:15.440
MATT RODBARD: That
was the kicker.

00:18:15.440 --> 00:18:17.130
HILLARY: Yeah.

00:18:17.130 --> 00:18:20.240
And seems like
attention to me, to make

00:18:20.240 --> 00:18:22.080
a cookbook about
Korean food based

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:25.277
in the restaurant world, when
maybe it's more home-oriented.

00:18:25.277 --> 00:18:26.860
And I'd love to hear
a little bit more

00:18:26.860 --> 00:18:29.230
about how you navigated
that question in terms

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:32.990
of what recipes to include,
how to create them.

00:18:32.990 --> 00:18:35.256
MATT RODBARD: I'll
take the first part,

00:18:35.256 --> 00:18:37.880
which is the difference in home
cooking and restaurant cooking.

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:41.630
And a lot of times-- I
mean I think home cooking

00:18:41.630 --> 00:18:43.480
is the best when it
comes to anything.

00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:45.960
Like if you're making
at home, it's fantastic.

00:18:45.960 --> 00:18:48.170
You're actually putting
it together yourself.

00:18:48.170 --> 00:18:50.350
You're going through
that process,

00:18:50.350 --> 00:18:52.802
be it painful or wonderful
or somewhere in between.

00:18:52.802 --> 00:18:55.010
And you're serving your
family and your friends food.

00:18:55.010 --> 00:18:56.159
That's a magical thing.

00:18:56.159 --> 00:18:58.200
So I think home cooking
is the best to be honest.

00:18:58.200 --> 00:18:59.408
Can we get there every night.

00:18:59.408 --> 00:19:00.069
Of course not.

00:19:00.069 --> 00:19:02.110
But for Korean food in
particular, a lot of times

00:19:02.110 --> 00:19:05.600
the restaurants-- you
know they're not doing it

00:19:05.600 --> 00:19:08.160
for the food and only the food.

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:09.960
They're doing it for
a variety of things.

00:19:09.960 --> 00:19:11.490
Mostly it's to make money.

00:19:11.490 --> 00:19:14.180
You know, Korean
Americans immigrated here

00:19:14.180 --> 00:19:18.580
starting in the '50s and '60s
and a big chunk in the '70s.

00:19:18.580 --> 00:19:21.530
And oftentimes
Koreans landed here

00:19:21.530 --> 00:19:24.170
and there wasn't a lot
of job opportunities.

00:19:24.170 --> 00:19:27.550
And one of the main jobs was
restaurants that they could do.

00:19:27.550 --> 00:19:29.520
And oftentimes they
had to make money

00:19:29.520 --> 00:19:30.870
and it was how they survived.

00:19:30.870 --> 00:19:34.590
So are corners cut
in those situations.

00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:36.560
In some cases, yes.

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:38.590
Is the food delicious,
yes. sometimes it's

00:19:38.590 --> 00:19:43.600
not as good as it would be if
you're buying every component.

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:45.370
Or buying the best
gochujang you could.

00:19:45.370 --> 00:19:47.130
Or buying the freshest produce.

00:19:47.130 --> 00:19:49.770
So that's the one big
difference between the two.

00:19:49.770 --> 00:19:52.680
I think folks need to
understand Korean food has

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:55.180
many different iterations
in the restaurant scene.

00:19:55.180 --> 00:19:57.290
And you cover restaurants
a lot, so we can maybe

00:19:57.290 --> 00:19:58.340
talk about that later.

00:19:58.340 --> 00:19:59.420
HILLARY: Yeah, for sure.

00:19:59.420 --> 00:20:00.380
MATT RODBARD: But the
other question for you

00:20:00.380 --> 00:20:02.255
is for the actual
development of the recipes.

00:20:02.255 --> 00:20:04.338
HILLARY: Yeah, for the
development of the recipes.

00:20:04.338 --> 00:20:07.080
Whether you thought of it more
in terms of the way things come

00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:08.704
together in a restaurant
versus the way

00:20:08.704 --> 00:20:09.850
they come together at home.

00:20:09.850 --> 00:20:12.183
DEUKI HONG:All right, so two
totally different mindsets.

00:20:12.183 --> 00:20:16.846
I think a lot of the recipes
developed in the book-- half

00:20:16.846 --> 00:20:18.220
are like from my
mom and half are

00:20:18.220 --> 00:20:19.615
like-- there's no
standardization

00:20:19.615 --> 00:20:21.060
in Korean cooking.

00:20:21.060 --> 00:20:24.750
You ask like a Korean
old guy or like a mom,

00:20:24.750 --> 00:20:27.230
they're like a little bit of
that, a little bit of this.

00:20:27.230 --> 00:20:28.730
MATT RODBARD: There's
a word for it.

00:20:28.730 --> 00:20:29.659
Son-mat, right?

00:20:29.659 --> 00:20:30.200
Hand cooking.

00:20:30.200 --> 00:20:30.630
DEUKI HONG: Son-mat.

00:20:30.630 --> 00:20:30.840
MATT RODBARD: Son-mat.

00:20:30.840 --> 00:20:32.670
Yeah, and It's like
hand cooking, right?

00:20:32.670 --> 00:20:33.378
DEUKI HONG: Yeah.

00:20:33.378 --> 00:20:36.022
Which is just a lazy way of,
I'm not going to measure it.

00:20:36.022 --> 00:20:37.809
Like, truth.

00:20:37.809 --> 00:20:38.350
I don't know.

00:20:38.350 --> 00:20:39.160
And that was hard.

00:20:39.160 --> 00:20:41.250
Because even when
we were cooking,

00:20:41.250 --> 00:20:42.690
I would just adopt that.

00:20:42.690 --> 00:20:45.222
So literally how we made
this book was, I cooked.

00:20:45.222 --> 00:20:46.930
Matty was right next
to me with a laptop.

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:48.300
Hey, what did you put in there.

00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:49.000
How much did you put in?

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:49.470
MATT RODBARD: Yeah

00:20:49.470 --> 00:20:50.090
DEUKI HONG: Did you put that in?

00:20:50.090 --> 00:20:51.320
Do I have to put that in?

00:20:51.320 --> 00:20:52.770
MATT RODBARD: Yeah, or tell me.

00:20:52.770 --> 00:20:53.740
Tell me now.

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:55.320
Like you're just like--

00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:56.280
DEUKI HONG: Like a
recipe that takes me

00:20:56.280 --> 00:20:57.950
fifteen minutes would take
like, literally two hours.

00:20:57.950 --> 00:20:59.330
MATT RODBARD: We need numbers.

00:20:59.330 --> 00:21:01.080
We're writing a cookbook,
we need numbers.

00:21:01.080 --> 00:21:02.746
DEUKI HONG: Yeah,
that's like his thing.

00:21:02.746 --> 00:21:03.690
Like people need this.

00:21:03.690 --> 00:21:07.240
I was like, no, just
a little bit of that.

00:21:07.240 --> 00:21:12.650
Because for me, you can't
measure salt. Or I don't know.

00:21:12.650 --> 00:21:14.746
Like it's just, you
just do it to taste.

00:21:14.746 --> 00:21:16.120
MATT RODBARD: Or
gochujang, even.

00:21:16.120 --> 00:21:16.957
A major component.

00:21:16.957 --> 00:21:18.540
HILLARY: Can you
explain what that is?

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:19.710
In case anybody--

00:21:19.710 --> 00:21:21.290
MATT RODBARD:
Fermented pepper paste.

00:21:21.290 --> 00:21:23.373
DEUKI HONG: Oh yeah, Korean
fermented chili paste.

00:21:23.373 --> 00:21:25.540
So like, Korean
food is pretty much

00:21:25.540 --> 00:21:28.776
based on the fermented
flavors, like jangs, right.

00:21:28.776 --> 00:21:31.810
So doenjang, soybean paste.

00:21:31.810 --> 00:21:33.800
Gochujang, which is
Korean chili paste.

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:35.925
It's kind of redundant
to say Korean.

00:21:35.925 --> 00:21:38.020
And then soy sauce,
ganjang, right.

00:21:38.020 --> 00:21:39.470
So those are kind of the three.

00:21:39.470 --> 00:21:40.880
And then everything else
kind of stems off of that.

00:21:40.880 --> 00:21:42.254
MATT RODBARD:
Branches off, yeah.

00:21:42.254 --> 00:21:44.810
HILLARY: So another topic
that you guys bring up pretty

00:21:44.810 --> 00:21:46.893
quickly in the intro to
the book is the importance

00:21:46.893 --> 00:21:48.610
of tradition in Korean cooking.

00:21:48.610 --> 00:21:51.910
And I was thinking about like
approaching this conversation

00:21:51.910 --> 00:21:54.690
being at Google where
creativity is paramount.

00:21:54.690 --> 00:21:56.280
Innovation is paramount.

00:21:56.280 --> 00:21:59.780
And where, when you're working
with these traditional recipes,

00:21:59.780 --> 00:22:02.420
was the room to bring
creativity and innovation,

00:22:02.420 --> 00:22:04.720
both to the book or to your
work in the restaurant?

00:22:04.720 --> 00:22:07.670
MATT RODBARD: Well when we were
working on the actual recipes,

00:22:07.670 --> 00:22:11.040
to Deuki's credit,
he was able to cut

00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:14.180
through a lot of the extra
steps needed for some

00:22:14.180 --> 00:22:16.240
of these complicated recipes.

00:22:16.240 --> 00:22:19.316
And you learn efficiency
in culinary school

00:22:19.316 --> 00:22:20.440
and in running restaurants.

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:23.079
And we went through the
most efficient route.

00:22:23.079 --> 00:22:24.495
And so that's a
creative approach.

00:22:24.495 --> 00:22:27.650
Not every recipe is a
slow way of doing it.

00:22:27.650 --> 00:22:28.220
That's one.

00:22:28.220 --> 00:22:30.460
But I think secondly,
we have this section

00:22:30.460 --> 00:22:34.310
in the book called Respect,
which shows how Korean food has

00:22:34.310 --> 00:22:37.830
expanded beyond Koreatown, or
the physical Koreatown that we

00:22:37.830 --> 00:22:38.330
know.

00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:39.980
So the last chapter
is called Respect

00:22:39.980 --> 00:22:42.990
and it has all these
guest recipes from chefs

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:44.310
throughout the country.

00:22:44.310 --> 00:22:46.974
And when we went out and
talked to our friends

00:22:46.974 --> 00:22:48.390
about the book
project, we weren't

00:22:48.390 --> 00:22:51.140
looking for 20 versions
of the kimchi taco.

00:22:51.140 --> 00:22:53.010
Or kimchi lasagna.

00:22:53.010 --> 00:22:56.030
We wanted like real
Korean food done

00:22:56.030 --> 00:22:59.470
in kind of an interesting
way, but from chefs

00:22:59.470 --> 00:23:00.630
who knew Korean food.

00:23:00.630 --> 00:23:04.270
So with that we've got like
Danny Bowen is doing this

00:23:04.270 --> 00:23:06.260
really cool, in our
book, has a recipe

00:23:06.260 --> 00:23:09.610
for a traditional Korean bone
broth called seolleongtang.

00:23:09.610 --> 00:23:12.950
But what he does is he
gussies it up with some uni,

00:23:12.950 --> 00:23:15.230
and he smokes brisket
and he puts it in there.

00:23:15.230 --> 00:23:17.750
And smoked pastrami.

00:23:17.750 --> 00:23:19.020
That's one example.

00:23:19.020 --> 00:23:20.245
Sean Brock for example--

00:23:20.245 --> 00:23:21.010
DEUKI HONG: It's a good recipe.

00:23:21.010 --> 00:23:22.676
MATT RODBARD: It's a
really good recipe.

00:23:22.676 --> 00:23:25.000
Sean Brock, who's a great
chef based in Nashville

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:31.740
and Charleston did a traditional
Korean pancake called pajeon,

00:23:31.740 --> 00:23:36.140
but he did it with corn meal
and with lowcountry shrimp.

00:23:36.140 --> 00:23:39.790
So I thought that was a really
cool way of understanding

00:23:39.790 --> 00:23:42.630
Korean food but then being
creative with the recipe.

00:23:42.630 --> 00:23:45.760
There's maybe 15 of those
recipes in the book.

00:23:45.760 --> 00:23:47.580
And it just shows
time and again how

00:23:47.580 --> 00:23:49.500
we chefs are thinking
about creating

00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:51.720
flavors but articulating
it in their own way.

00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:53.470
HILLARY: I think talking
about the respect

00:23:53.470 --> 00:23:56.380
section of the book, which
again is the recipes contributed

00:23:56.380 --> 00:23:58.560
by chefs who are not
necessarily known for cooking

00:23:58.560 --> 00:24:01.190
Korean food-- with a
capital K and a capital

00:24:01.190 --> 00:24:05.870
C-- I think there's
definitely room to grow,

00:24:05.870 --> 00:24:08.470
but it's very fair to
say that there has never

00:24:08.470 --> 00:24:11.450
been more interest in
America in Korean cuisine

00:24:11.450 --> 00:24:14.410
than there is right now.

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:16.290
And I'm wondering why.

00:24:16.290 --> 00:24:18.270
Like why Korean cuisine now?

00:24:18.270 --> 00:24:19.429
MATT RODBARD: Oh.

00:24:19.429 --> 00:24:20.470
DEUKI HONG: I don't know.

00:24:20.470 --> 00:24:21.350
MATT RODBARD: Yeah.

00:24:21.350 --> 00:24:23.712
DEUKI HONG: This is just--
we talked to a lot of chefs.

00:24:23.712 --> 00:24:24.420
And we travelled.

00:24:24.420 --> 00:24:26.880
The element of this
book-- it kind of

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:28.160
lends itself well to travel.

00:24:28.160 --> 00:24:30.064
And I've been
blessed enough to be

00:24:30.064 --> 00:24:31.480
in some of these
like top kitchens

00:24:31.480 --> 00:24:32.940
and I'd like stay
there for a day

00:24:32.940 --> 00:24:34.500
and like pick the chefs brain.

00:24:34.500 --> 00:24:37.840
And we're talking about
like when we're in DC

00:24:37.840 --> 00:24:40.230
and I'm with Eric-Bruner Yang.

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:42.160
These guys are like
the city icons.

00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:45.620
Or like in charge of the food
movement in their cities.

00:24:45.620 --> 00:24:47.509
And I asked them.

00:24:47.509 --> 00:24:49.300
But you realize like
this is what they eat.

00:24:49.300 --> 00:24:50.677
Like they're not eating like--

00:24:50.677 --> 00:24:51.760
MATT RODBARD: French food.

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:53.218
DEUKI HONG: Sean
Brock isn't eating

00:24:53.218 --> 00:24:54.380
like chicken and waffles.

00:24:54.380 --> 00:24:56.160
Like country whatever.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:24:59.950
He's eating Korean food and
he's like fermenting kimchi.

00:24:59.950 --> 00:25:03.090
And you just appreciate
like this is going on.

00:25:03.090 --> 00:25:06.744
Just nobody-- I don't
want to say nobody

00:25:06.744 --> 00:25:08.910
cared, but like nobody
thought to ask that question.

00:25:08.910 --> 00:25:11.160
Like what do you eat outside
of-- you just think like,

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:14.340
oh Eric Ripert, he probably eats
like very fancy French seafood

00:25:14.340 --> 00:25:15.300
of some sort.

00:25:15.300 --> 00:25:17.270
Probably cooks himself
the most perfect fish--

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:18.103
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:25:18.103 --> 00:25:20.109
DEUKI HONG: But he's
eating Korean food.

00:25:20.109 --> 00:25:22.150
He's eating Korean like,
Buddhist temple cuisine.

00:25:22.150 --> 00:25:24.001
And you know you're
just like, oh, this

00:25:24.001 --> 00:25:25.000
is like kind of awesome.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:29.386
And for me, the respect
chapter, as a kid in the game,

00:25:29.386 --> 00:25:32.652
it's freaking awesome.

00:25:32.652 --> 00:25:34.110
It's like being a
basketball player

00:25:34.110 --> 00:25:37.890
and then having
LeBron and Curry,

00:25:37.890 --> 00:25:42.140
because we're in Curryland,
signing your yearbook, right?

00:25:42.140 --> 00:25:45.106
Congrats on y'all, by the way.

00:25:45.106 --> 00:25:45.840
Kobe by the way.

00:25:45.840 --> 00:25:47.510
So it's like for me,
I'm just like, what, why

00:25:47.510 --> 00:25:48.290
is he in the book?

00:25:48.290 --> 00:25:51.160
Like not in a bad way.

00:25:51.160 --> 00:25:53.360
Like Eric Ripert, Danny
Bowien, all these people

00:25:53.360 --> 00:25:55.500
like we get to call now
because we're like, chef,

00:25:55.500 --> 00:25:57.640
can I talk to you
about Korean food?

00:25:57.640 --> 00:26:00.285
MATT RODBARD: Stu
Brioza, he's in the book

00:26:00.285 --> 00:26:02.920
and he has a really cool
dish with yuba and house-made

00:26:02.920 --> 00:26:03.763
kimchi.

00:26:03.763 --> 00:26:05.320
DEUKI HONG: Such an incredible
meal yesterday at Statebird's.

00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:07.528
MATT RODBARD: Yeah and he's
cooking with kimchi there

00:26:07.528 --> 00:26:11.480
and cooking with
inspiration and adventure.

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:14.780
But I will add too, that
where Korean food is

00:26:14.780 --> 00:26:17.480
right now in the restaurant
world nationally,

00:26:17.480 --> 00:26:20.030
there's a lot of
Korean-American chefs like Deuki

00:26:20.030 --> 00:26:22.930
who are cooking the foods
that they grew up on.

00:26:22.930 --> 00:26:26.030
Folks like Beverly
Kim in Chicago.

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:29.280
Edward Lee in
Louisville, Kentucky.

00:26:29.280 --> 00:26:31.810
And Edward Kim in Mott
Street in Chicago.

00:26:31.810 --> 00:26:32.880
These are great examples.

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:33.765
There's many of
them who are cooking

00:26:33.765 --> 00:26:35.060
these traditional flavors.

00:26:35.060 --> 00:26:37.900
Chefs who maybe came from more
of a traditional background,

00:26:37.900 --> 00:26:40.930
like a French background or
a fancy Italian background,

00:26:40.930 --> 00:26:43.310
and they're actually
rediscovering

00:26:43.310 --> 00:26:48.270
their own internal
recipe book but then

00:26:48.270 --> 00:26:53.420
presenting them to the public
in kind of an uncompromised way.

00:26:53.420 --> 00:26:56.730
And that's super exciting to be
seeing these traditional dishes

00:26:56.730 --> 00:26:58.860
come to life.

00:26:58.860 --> 00:27:01.530
HILLARY: I want to talk a little
bit about flavor with that too.

00:27:01.530 --> 00:27:03.030
Because one of the
things that I've

00:27:03.030 --> 00:27:04.779
been wondering about
as I've been thinking

00:27:04.779 --> 00:27:07.004
more about Korean food and
why there's this uptick is

00:27:07.004 --> 00:27:09.170
I definitely think there's
a little bit of a chicken

00:27:09.170 --> 00:27:09.830
and egg.

00:27:09.830 --> 00:27:11.470
Where it's like
well, chefs love it.

00:27:11.470 --> 00:27:13.011
And they're telling
people, you know.

00:27:13.011 --> 00:27:14.650
And that's why
customers love it.

00:27:14.650 --> 00:27:17.439
But I also think that
one of the-- and you

00:27:17.439 --> 00:27:18.980
talk about this so
much in the book--

00:27:18.980 --> 00:27:22.270
a real pillar of
Korean cooking is

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:24.690
fermentation and the
process of fermentation

00:27:24.690 --> 00:27:30.440
and then the flavors that
arise from fermentation

00:27:30.440 --> 00:27:31.870
really carries the food.

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:36.940
And sort of America's
interest in fermented foods

00:27:36.940 --> 00:27:38.720
is really on the rise right.

00:27:38.720 --> 00:27:40.959
So for me, that was
sort of a through line

00:27:40.959 --> 00:27:42.750
that I've been seeing
and thinking about it

00:27:42.750 --> 00:27:43.541
as I read the book.

00:27:43.541 --> 00:27:47.880
And as I'm thinking about why
chefs who don't necessarily

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:51.290
have a Korean background
or even a background

00:27:51.290 --> 00:27:53.173
cooking that kind of
food or maybe dabbling.

00:27:55.900 --> 00:27:57.230
Is America's palate expanding?

00:27:59.772 --> 00:28:02.230
MATT RODBARD: I'll say that
just that Asian food in general

00:28:02.230 --> 00:28:03.060
is expanding.

00:28:03.060 --> 00:28:09.180
And Americans love these Eastern
Asian flavors, soy sauce,

00:28:09.180 --> 00:28:12.000
fermented jangs,
be it Korean jangs

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:15.830
or Chinese fermented pastes.

00:28:15.830 --> 00:28:21.050
You know, noodles from
Asia, ramen's kicked it off,

00:28:21.050 --> 00:28:24.800
but now lots of pho--
you're seeing these flavors.

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:28.810
These sours, these very
like Asian flavors.

00:28:28.810 --> 00:28:29.890
Fish sauce for example.

00:28:29.890 --> 00:28:30.790
You're seeing fish
sauce everywhere.

00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:32.665
You're seeing fish sauce
on brussels sprouts.

00:28:32.665 --> 00:28:34.530
I mean brussels
sprouts aren't part

00:28:34.530 --> 00:28:39.570
of the Asian like
vegetable category.

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:42.690
So I think you're just
seeing the American palate

00:28:42.690 --> 00:28:43.549
is changing.

00:28:43.549 --> 00:28:45.590
I mean, you see it in your
restaurant too, right?

00:28:45.590 --> 00:28:50.970
DEUKI HONG: Yeah, I mean it
started for me in '09 when I

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:52.335
was working at JG and--

00:28:52.335 --> 00:28:53.460
MATT RODBARD: Jean-Georges.

00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:55.700
DEUKI HONG: Jean-Georges, sorry.

00:28:55.700 --> 00:28:59.540
And the chef, their corporate
chef there, Chef Greg Brannon--

00:28:59.540 --> 00:29:03.300
his palate is like, it's-- it's
just I've met so many people

00:29:03.300 --> 00:29:05.050
that are like the
masters of like--

00:29:05.050 --> 00:29:06.307
Serpico is like the guy--

00:29:06.307 --> 00:29:08.640
HILLARY: Who's also going to
open a Korean Small Plates.

00:29:08.640 --> 00:29:09.160
DEUKI HONG: He is.

00:29:09.160 --> 00:29:09.885
MATT RODBARD: Oh yeah.

00:29:09.885 --> 00:29:11.070
HILLARY: In Philadelphia,
for his second Philadelphia

00:29:11.070 --> 00:29:11.140
restaurant.

00:29:11.140 --> 00:29:12.030
MATT RODBARD: That's
another good one, yeah.

00:29:12.030 --> 00:29:12.310
Sorry,

00:29:12.310 --> 00:29:14.390
HILLARY: We're talking
about Peter Serpico, who

00:29:14.390 --> 00:29:17.690
is a long-time Lieutenant in
David Chang's Momofuku empire

00:29:17.690 --> 00:29:20.770
and is now a restaurant owner
and operator in Philadelphia.

00:29:20.770 --> 00:29:22.090
DEUKI HONG: He's like a fish.

00:29:22.090 --> 00:29:24.631
Like, you watch the guy break
down fish and you're just like,

00:29:24.631 --> 00:29:25.970
I could watch this all day.

00:29:25.970 --> 00:29:27.934
And I'm working right
next to these guys.

00:29:27.934 --> 00:29:30.100
I was with Chef Greg and I
made him some Korean dish

00:29:30.100 --> 00:29:31.207
for family meal.

00:29:31.207 --> 00:29:32.540
And then he said the same thing.

00:29:32.540 --> 00:29:33.998
He's like, I don't
understand why--

00:29:33.998 --> 00:29:37.450
and this is seven
years ago-- isn't

00:29:37.450 --> 00:29:40.514
Korean food-- like every
flavor profile of Korean food--

00:29:40.514 --> 00:29:41.680
it hits what Americans like.

00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:43.065
Sweet, savory, spicy.

00:29:43.782 --> 00:29:46.240
And I said, I was like, chef,
I don't know, I'm just a kid.

00:29:46.240 --> 00:29:48.450
I don't know.

00:29:48.450 --> 00:29:53.170
But I understand it more
and more now because there's

00:29:53.170 --> 00:29:54.960
nothing crazy about it.

00:29:54.960 --> 00:29:56.530
We're not doing anything crazy.

00:29:56.530 --> 00:29:59.600
The food existed for a while.

00:29:59.600 --> 00:30:02.210
I just go back to that
kind of fermentation flavor

00:30:02.210 --> 00:30:04.480
and I just think it's
that extra layer of umami

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:07.280
where you can't fabricate it.

00:30:07.280 --> 00:30:08.670
You can, I mean in MSG.

00:30:08.670 --> 00:30:09.390
But you can't.

00:30:09.390 --> 00:30:10.450
It's different.

00:30:10.450 --> 00:30:13.470
When you taste a really good
doenjang, and you taste soup

00:30:13.470 --> 00:30:15.129
that comes out of
that doenjang--

00:30:15.129 --> 00:30:16.170
that took months to make.

00:30:16.170 --> 00:30:16.860
That took time.

00:30:19.030 --> 00:30:24.707
It's different than miso, which
is no knock on miso, just--

