I'm just saying.

00:32:54.700 --> 00:32:56.658
MATT RODBARD: Yeah, I've
got a very good friend

00:32:56.658 --> 00:32:59.320
who lives in Oakland, who was
my gateway to Korean food.

00:32:59.320 --> 00:33:01.720
But I think everyone has
that and it's so beautiful

00:33:01.720 --> 00:33:04.810
to go to a restaurant to have
your Korean best friend show

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:06.570
you all the dishes.

00:33:06.570 --> 00:33:10.720
Not just the barbecue but order
of like kalbijjim or something

00:33:10.720 --> 00:33:11.444
cool like that.

00:33:11.444 --> 00:33:13.360
DEUKI HONG: Sorry, who
comes to my restaurant.

00:33:13.360 --> 00:33:16.580
A lot of people come
to the restaurant.

00:33:16.580 --> 00:33:21.360
And that's crazy because we
serve a lot of people a day.

00:33:21.360 --> 00:33:24.060
And y'all know in the back how
much because they serve Google.

00:33:24.060 --> 00:33:25.920
But we do those kind of numbers.

00:33:25.920 --> 00:33:28.807
Like I'm not used to it.

00:33:28.807 --> 00:33:30.640
The biggest restaurant
I've worked for was I

00:33:30.640 --> 00:33:33.185
think, it was Momofuku,
it was the noodle bar.

00:33:33.185 --> 00:33:34.560
HILLARY: You mean
by just volume?

00:33:34.560 --> 00:33:36.530
DEUKI HONG: Yeah,
it was just lines.

00:33:36.530 --> 00:33:39.434
And it's like one of
those good worries.

00:33:39.434 --> 00:33:41.600
Like, why are you complaining
about people lining up

00:33:41.600 --> 00:33:42.391
at your restaurant.

00:33:42.391 --> 00:33:46.790
But it's kind of like, for me
I don't need to fill a quota.

00:33:46.790 --> 00:33:49.400
You know if we're
feeding 100 people,

00:33:49.400 --> 00:33:51.484
I want it to be a damn
good meal, you know.

00:33:51.484 --> 00:33:52.900
But I think it's
harder to control

00:33:52.900 --> 00:33:54.620
when you get to the 600.

00:33:54.620 --> 00:33:56.795
And on the weekends, like 900.

00:33:56.795 --> 00:33:58.170
MATT RODBARD: And
to your credit,

00:33:58.170 --> 00:34:00.378
when you go to Kang Ho Dong
Baekjeong, his restaurant

00:34:00.378 --> 00:34:02.650
in New York, you're having
doenjang jigae, which is

00:34:02.650 --> 00:34:04.510
the fermented bean paste stew.

00:34:04.510 --> 00:34:06.280
And it's like the
best in the city.

00:34:06.280 --> 00:34:08.540
And he's doing it
for 900 a night.

00:34:08.540 --> 00:34:10.010
And it's crazy to do that.

00:34:10.010 --> 00:34:10.969
That volume.

00:34:10.969 --> 00:34:13.656
I mean it's really,
really impressive.

00:34:13.656 --> 00:34:15.989
DEUKI HONG: I mean, it's not
easy and we want to cut it.

00:34:15.989 --> 00:34:18.760
Like we were even talking
about like, should be like stop

00:34:18.760 --> 00:34:21.150
accepting reservations.

00:34:21.150 --> 00:34:24.790
And stop accepting people
at a certain amount

00:34:24.790 --> 00:34:28.712
just to like quality,
like how ramen shops do.

00:34:28.712 --> 00:34:30.170
But we realized
that we don't care.

00:34:30.170 --> 00:34:31.644
We're just like,
just serve everybody.

00:34:31.644 --> 00:34:32.510
HILLARY: Like make it work.

00:34:32.510 --> 00:34:33.580
DEUKI HONG: Yeah, make it work.

00:34:33.580 --> 00:34:34.280
Exactly.

00:34:34.280 --> 00:34:35.510
Like forget that.

00:34:35.510 --> 00:34:37.429
Just make it work.

00:34:37.429 --> 00:34:38.920
But a lot of
awesome people come.

00:34:38.920 --> 00:34:40.770
I mean, we've been
embraced by the industry.

00:34:40.770 --> 00:34:43.360
And I think that's
our biggest-- I

00:34:43.360 --> 00:34:47.460
cook for-- like I can't
read-- the last time I clicked

00:34:47.460 --> 00:34:50.580
into Yelp and read our or
any restaurant that I've

00:34:50.580 --> 00:34:53.810
worked at review was a
really long time ago.

00:34:53.810 --> 00:34:54.729
I just don't do it.

00:34:54.729 --> 00:34:56.520
I don't know of many
industry people do it.

00:35:00.040 --> 00:35:01.690
I cook for the industry people.

00:35:01.690 --> 00:35:04.070
And I don't know if
that's right or wrong.

00:35:04.070 --> 00:35:05.080
I don't care.

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:06.690
I cook for chefs.

00:35:06.690 --> 00:35:08.480
I cook for industry.

00:35:08.480 --> 00:35:10.572
I love industry people.

00:35:10.572 --> 00:35:12.280
Not that I don't care
about anybody else.

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:13.870
It's that I focus on them.

00:35:13.870 --> 00:35:17.930
I use that expensive
cut of meat because I'm

00:35:17.930 --> 00:35:21.390
sure chef is going to come and
he deserves a nice cut of meat.

00:35:21.390 --> 00:35:24.590
I'm not going to go use
that cheaper cut to save

00:35:24.590 --> 00:35:27.640
a little bit here because
I feel like there's

00:35:27.640 --> 00:35:30.910
this fraternity and this
camaraderie where I trust you,

00:35:30.910 --> 00:35:32.040
you trust me type of deal.

00:35:32.040 --> 00:35:34.206
Where I trust you enough
and I go to your restaurant

00:35:34.206 --> 00:35:36.000
and there's that element.

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:39.414
But I feel like I cook for
chefs in New York City.

00:35:39.414 --> 00:35:41.580
HILLARY: So that's really
a question about audience.

00:35:41.580 --> 00:35:45.370
And who your audience is and
which part of your audience

00:35:45.370 --> 00:35:48.360
you are focusing on.

00:35:48.360 --> 00:35:52.820
How did you guys imagine
the audience for the book?

00:35:52.820 --> 00:35:55.272
And who were you writing for?

00:35:55.272 --> 00:35:56.480
MATT RODBARD: Great question.

00:35:56.480 --> 00:36:01.870
So I think we were looking to
capture a few audiences first

00:36:01.870 --> 00:36:03.405
and foremost Korean-Americans.

00:36:03.405 --> 00:36:05.530
I think there's a lot of
Korean-Americans out there

00:36:05.530 --> 00:36:08.400
who know the dishes but
don't know how to make them

00:36:08.400 --> 00:36:10.020
but are dabbling into food.

00:36:10.020 --> 00:36:11.930
I think you're seeing
a lot of young folks

00:36:11.930 --> 00:36:14.620
who are you subscribing
to Blue Apron

00:36:14.620 --> 00:36:19.590
or maybe buying a cookbook and
experimenting with cooking.

00:36:19.590 --> 00:36:22.630
But a lot of Korean-Americans
have the books

00:36:22.630 --> 00:36:24.590
that tell you how to make it.

00:36:24.590 --> 00:36:25.850
So that was one audience.

00:36:25.850 --> 00:36:31.010
But then the bigger audience
was fans of Asian food.

00:36:31.010 --> 00:36:34.050
Like people who line up
for the ramen burger.

00:36:34.050 --> 00:36:38.160
Or go down to San Gabriel
Valley in Los Angeles

00:36:38.160 --> 00:36:41.390
or out to San Jose to have the
Vietnamese food or whatever.

00:36:41.390 --> 00:36:44.889
You know, those folks,
whoever they may be,

00:36:44.889 --> 00:36:46.680
we're writing that book
for them because we

00:36:46.680 --> 00:36:50.510
want them to see that Korean
food has a lot of personality

00:36:50.510 --> 00:36:53.240
and there's a lot of
intricacies there.

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:54.082
And we did the work.

00:36:54.082 --> 00:36:56.290
We went through all these
dishes and told the stories

00:36:56.290 --> 00:36:57.040
in the head notes.

00:36:57.040 --> 00:36:58.480
And so it's for that audience.

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:01.030
And then I don't know, who else?

00:37:01.030 --> 00:37:03.870
DEUKI HONG: I just like
did it to our friends.

00:37:03.870 --> 00:37:06.710
We don't reach like--
I shouldn't say that,

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:09.630
I have to-- we're not like
one of these beautiful,

00:37:09.630 --> 00:37:11.380
illustrious--

00:37:11.380 --> 00:37:13.940
MATT RODBARD: Domnique Crenn's
book, which is an amazing.

00:37:13.940 --> 00:37:16.390
HILLARY: This is not
a coffee table book.

00:37:16.390 --> 00:37:18.140
It's a book that can get dirty.

00:37:18.140 --> 00:37:19.230
MATT RODBARD: It's a bit
of a nightstand book,

00:37:19.230 --> 00:37:19.740
I'd like to say.

00:37:19.740 --> 00:37:20.860
You can actually read it.

00:37:20.860 --> 00:37:22.670
HILLARY: It's a good read.

00:37:22.670 --> 00:37:25.020
And it's not too precious.

00:37:25.020 --> 00:37:25.120
So I feel like you
can spill on it.

00:37:25.120 --> 00:37:26.620
DEUKI HONG: I feel
like the language

00:37:26.620 --> 00:37:30.350
we use-- at least audience,
I wasn't like let's target

00:37:30.350 --> 00:37:31.615
like 25 to 35.

00:37:34.900 --> 00:37:37.910
The language, to Matt's
credit-- and I love the way

00:37:37.910 --> 00:37:39.270
he writes too.

00:37:39.270 --> 00:37:42.874
It's like talking
to your friend.

00:37:42.874 --> 00:37:44.290
You're not going
to see that book.

00:37:44.290 --> 00:37:47.380
It's not like some
encyclopedia, like a formal--

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:50.832
there's a bit of salty
language in there.

00:37:50.832 --> 00:37:52.415
MATT RODBARD: One
reviewer on Amazon--

00:37:52.415 --> 00:37:54.300
DEUKI HONG: So we
got an Amazon review.

00:37:54.300 --> 00:37:56.570
She e-mailed us.

00:37:56.570 --> 00:37:58.709
She was like a mother
in the middle America.

00:37:58.709 --> 00:38:01.000
And we're just grateful that
somebody in middle America

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:01.540
heard about us.

00:38:01.540 --> 00:38:03.040
MATT RODBARD: And
I'm from Michigan.

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:04.080
From Middle America too.

00:38:04.080 --> 00:38:05.780
DEUKI HONG: But she
has like ten kids.

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:07.700
And she was like,
oh, I love your book.

00:38:07.700 --> 00:38:08.570
I love your recipes.

00:38:08.570 --> 00:38:10.890
But I'm so disappointed
in you Deuki.

00:38:10.890 --> 00:38:12.135
You're using salty language.

00:38:12.135 --> 00:38:13.510
And I was like,
what is going on.

00:38:13.510 --> 00:38:14.120
MATT RODBARD: What is going on.

00:38:14.120 --> 00:38:15.970
DEUKI HONG: Like, Matty
did you swear on my behalf?

00:38:15.970 --> 00:38:17.345
MATT RODBARD: And
Deuki literally

00:38:17.345 --> 00:38:18.740
went through it
every single page

00:38:18.740 --> 00:38:22.810
to see where the
salty language was.

00:38:22.810 --> 00:38:27.496
But really, what happened was
that's David Chang's quote.

00:38:27.496 --> 00:38:28.870
DEUKI HONG: So
what happened was,

00:38:28.870 --> 00:38:31.090
there's literally four
pages in our whole book.

00:38:31.090 --> 00:38:34.250
And I can name you those
pages, 87, 163, 164, and 202

00:38:34.250 --> 00:38:37.320
or something like that.

00:38:37.320 --> 00:38:40.930
And two of those pages is the
interview with Chef Chang.

00:38:40.930 --> 00:38:43.310
And like you can't
filter that guy.

00:38:43.310 --> 00:38:46.960
So I think she might have
confused the two Asians.

00:38:46.960 --> 00:38:48.740
And like, oh that's
probably him.

00:38:48.740 --> 00:38:49.907
So we don't blame you, Abby.

00:38:49.907 --> 00:38:51.281
She bought the
book and you know,

00:38:51.281 --> 00:38:52.932
she was like very
disappointed in us.

00:38:52.932 --> 00:38:54.390
I was really sad
for the whole day.

00:38:54.390 --> 00:38:55.650
I was like, oh man.

00:38:55.650 --> 00:38:56.020
MATT RODBARD: I know.

00:38:56.020 --> 00:38:57.936
DEUKI HONG: There's a
family in middle America

00:38:57.936 --> 00:39:00.020
that thinks I'm really horrible.

00:39:00.020 --> 00:39:03.430
MATT RODBARD: Voice is really
important though with writing.

00:39:03.430 --> 00:39:04.625
And I think we captured it.

00:39:04.625 --> 00:39:07.000
And thank you for the praise,
but it's really both of us.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:09.740
It's me interviewing
Deuki and recording it,

00:39:09.740 --> 00:39:11.920
and then transcribing it,
and having that in there.

00:39:11.920 --> 00:39:13.380
Or just us being together a lot.

00:39:13.380 --> 00:39:16.115
It's almost like osmosis, it
comes between, into my brain

00:39:16.115 --> 00:39:16.940
and into yours.

00:39:16.940 --> 00:39:22.500
And we express ourselves in the
book truthfully and honestly.

00:39:22.500 --> 00:39:25.170
And that's hard to do
in a lot of writing.

00:39:25.170 --> 00:39:26.935
And credit to our
editor for not--

00:39:26.935 --> 00:39:28.060
DEUKI HONG: Editing it out.

00:39:28.060 --> 00:39:29.660
Not cleaning up anything.

00:39:29.660 --> 00:39:30.576
MATT RODBARD: Yeah.

00:39:30.576 --> 00:39:32.200
DEUKI HONG: It's like
if you called us.

