00:51:40.844 --> 00:51:41.760
you need to come here.

00:51:41.760 --> 00:51:43.370
MATT RODBARD: Yeah,
I like that idea.

00:51:43.370 --> 00:51:45.626
DEUKI HONG: Chef Danny
is a good friend.

00:51:45.626 --> 00:51:46.492
And Chef Corey.

00:51:46.492 --> 00:51:48.200
MATT RODBARD: Let's
talk about Corey Lee.

00:51:48.200 --> 00:51:49.100
HILLARY: Oh yeah, let do that.

00:51:49.100 --> 00:51:49.820
Let's talk about Corey Lee.

00:51:49.820 --> 00:51:51.010
He's the chef of benu.

00:51:51.010 --> 00:51:52.659
He just got his
third Michelin star.

00:51:52.659 --> 00:51:53.950
MATT RODBARD: Korean-Americans.

00:51:53.950 --> 00:51:54.360
DEUKI HONG: I love Corey Lee.

00:51:54.360 --> 00:51:56.276
That's all I have to say
about Chef Corey Lee.

00:51:56.276 --> 00:51:58.250
I admire that man.

00:51:58.250 --> 00:52:01.020
I worship the ground
that he walks on.

00:52:01.020 --> 00:52:02.500
To put it lightly

00:52:02.500 --> 00:52:05.300
HILLARY: I think for just
a little more background,

00:52:05.300 --> 00:52:09.320
the food that he's doing at
benu-- sort of in the same way

00:52:09.320 --> 00:52:12.320
that you see chefs of
Korean-American heritage

00:52:12.320 --> 00:52:15.902
in America-- they wouldn't
say like, no I'm not

00:52:15.902 --> 00:52:17.860
cooking Korean food, I'm
cooking American food.

00:52:17.860 --> 00:52:20.276
And for me, American food means
flavors from my childhood.

00:52:20.276 --> 00:52:22.180
Ingredients from where I live.

00:52:22.180 --> 00:52:25.870
And techniques that
I grew up using.

00:52:25.870 --> 00:52:30.194
So somebody like a
David Chang for example,

00:52:30.194 --> 00:52:31.610
you feel like he's
in conversation

00:52:31.610 --> 00:52:33.170
with what Corey Lee is doing.

00:52:33.170 --> 00:52:34.461
DEUKI HONG: That's great point.

00:52:36.690 --> 00:52:40.220
HILLARY: And I think Dave
brought up Corey in your book

00:52:40.220 --> 00:52:40.971
in that interview.

00:52:40.971 --> 00:52:43.469
MATT RODBARD: Oh I think he has
a similar opinion that Deuki

00:52:43.469 --> 00:52:44.530
has that Corey's doing.

00:52:44.530 --> 00:52:44.970
DEUKI HONG: I mean
not that intense.

00:52:44.970 --> 00:52:45.900
MATT RODBARD: Not that intense.

00:52:45.900 --> 00:52:47.390
But he's in a very
important figure

00:52:47.390 --> 00:52:50.400
in talking about
Korean food in America.

00:52:50.400 --> 00:52:53.127
And he's here in San Francisco.

00:52:53.127 --> 00:52:54.210
I like Brother's Barbecue.

00:52:54.210 --> 00:52:55.820
That's another place.

00:52:55.820 --> 00:52:58.500
I think that's fantastic.

00:52:58.500 --> 00:53:00.910
HILLARY: But I have to say
this one thing about benu.

00:53:00.910 --> 00:53:03.530
They do this dish.

00:53:03.530 --> 00:53:05.580
When it arrives at your
table, it's teeny tiny.

00:53:05.580 --> 00:53:08.870
And it's this like
see through red shell

00:53:08.870 --> 00:53:11.440
on top of which
you see an oyster.

00:53:11.440 --> 00:53:14.790
And you bite it and you're like,
I've had these flavors before.

00:53:14.790 --> 00:53:16.330
This is like, what is this.

00:53:16.330 --> 00:53:18.530
Well it turns out
see through shell

00:53:18.530 --> 00:53:19.990
somehow was made of kimchi.

00:53:19.990 --> 00:53:21.700
And there was also
pork in there.

00:53:21.700 --> 00:53:24.510
And it's like this
little baby bossam bite.

00:53:24.510 --> 00:53:25.710
But you know, it's magical.

00:53:25.710 --> 00:53:27.751
DEUKI HONG: Chef Corey
Lee, ladies and gentlemen.

00:53:27.751 --> 00:53:30.030
Corey Lee.

00:53:30.030 --> 00:53:31.230
I wasn't fortunate enough.

00:53:31.230 --> 00:53:33.037
I had to save about
seven paychecks.

00:53:33.037 --> 00:53:34.370
HILLARY: I went with my brother.

00:53:34.370 --> 00:53:35.427
He's a lawyer.

00:53:35.427 --> 00:53:36.510
MATT RODBARD: That's true.

00:53:36.510 --> 00:53:40.980
But really like the
classic flavors being

00:53:40.980 --> 00:53:42.582
done in an interesting way.

00:53:42.582 --> 00:53:45.040
I think that's really the future
of Korean food in America.

00:53:45.040 --> 00:53:47.350
You're going to see
it time and again.

00:53:47.350 --> 00:53:48.860
It's just the
traditional flavors.

00:53:48.860 --> 00:53:50.716
Not fusion.

00:53:50.716 --> 00:53:53.160
Not like kimchi grilled cheese.

00:53:53.160 --> 00:53:54.077
It's not that.

00:53:54.077 --> 00:53:55.370
DEUKI HONG: Hating on the
taco and the grilled cheese.

00:53:55.370 --> 00:53:56.203
MATT RODBARD: Sorry.

00:53:57.146 --> 00:53:58.520
HILLARY: So yes
in San Francisco,

00:53:58.520 --> 00:54:01.510
we were saying-- one
answer to that question

00:54:01.510 --> 00:54:04.210
of where can you find Korean
flavor in San Francisco is at

00:54:04.210 --> 00:54:07.720
benu, if you're fortunate
enough to be able to go.

00:54:07.720 --> 00:54:09.710
And then you were saying
Brother's Barbecue.

00:54:09.710 --> 00:54:11.912
MATT RODBARD: Yeah, and
that's in Richmond, right?

00:54:11.912 --> 00:54:12.620
It's a good spot.

00:54:12.620 --> 00:54:13.270
I went there--

00:54:13.270 --> 00:54:15.294
DEUKI HONG: We know no
places in San Francisco.

00:54:15.294 --> 00:54:17.210
We're like trying to
pull to you, we're like--

00:54:17.210 --> 00:54:18.610
MATT RODBARD: We didn't
spend too much time eating

00:54:18.610 --> 00:54:20.080
at Korean restaurants here.

00:54:20.080 --> 00:54:23.030
LA was such an important
part, we went there mostly.

00:54:23.030 --> 00:54:26.960
But I had a really good chance
to visit with Adam Johnson,

00:54:26.960 --> 00:54:30.250
who wrote Orphan Master's Son,
who won a Pulitzer in 2013,

00:54:30.250 --> 00:54:32.146
and we had a meal at Brother's.

00:54:32.146 --> 00:54:33.270
And I thought it was great.

00:54:33.270 --> 00:54:34.894
They make their own
time doenjang there

00:54:34.894 --> 00:54:36.900
and it's charcoal BBQ.

00:54:36.900 --> 00:54:38.494
It's a good one.

